What works and what doesn't in Connect mode.

The dataframe and sql ay-pee-eyes are the supported surface. That is deliberate, because those describe a plan that can be serialized. Anything that depends on direct java virtual machine access from the client cannot work.

Things that work include all dataframe and dataset operations, the spark dot sql call, the read and write methods, the entire built-in functions library, pandas user defined functions, regular Python user defined functions, structured streaming since three point five, and the pandas ay-pee-eye on Spark since three point five. Most catalog listings work too.

Things that do not work include direct access to spark context, the entire r-d-d ay-pee-eye, internal Py-four-J handles like spark underscore j-v-m and spark underscore j-s-c, and adding jars from the client at runtime. Jars must already be on the server classpath.

The takeaway for the exam: if a question mentions spark context, r-d-d, or injecting jars from the client, that code is incompatible with Spark Connect. If it sticks to dataframe, sql, and built-in or registered user defined functions, it works.
